Carbon monoxide (CO) is an invisible, odorless byproduct of combustion caused mainly by motor vehicles.CO can trigger headaches or aggravate heart disease.

Nitrogen dioxide (NO2) is produced by fuel burning, especially by motor vehicles. NO2 inflames the lungs, causes coughing and wheezing, increases vulnerability to lung infections and can make asthma attacks more intense and frequent.
High concentrations of ozone can cause headaches and irritate the lungs and airways, aggravating conditions such as asthma and chronic bronchitis.
Large particles called PM10 irritate the eyes, nose, and respiratory system.
Tiny particles called PM2.5 irritate the eyes, nose, and respiratory system. Long-term exposure aggravates heart and lung disease.
Sulfur dioxide (SO2) is emitted mainly by large facilities such as coal-burning power plants. Exposure to high concentrations of SO2 can make breathing more difficult.

"The force exerted by the weight of the atmosphere. High pressure often signifies pleasant weather, whereas low pressure systems often signify eventful weather conditions. Weather Underground reports pressure measurements that are adjusted for sea levels. This makes it possible to compare pressure readings from different elevations."
"Your phone's pressure readings will appear in the Details tile. Data will be sent anonymously in the background."
